## GitHub CLI SSH Key Management

The `gh ssh-key` command manages SSH keys registered with your GitHub account.

### Adding SSH Keys

To add an SSH key to your GitHub account, use the `ssh-key add` subcommand, specifying your public key. The basic syntax is `gh ssh-key add [<key-file>]` with options for `--title` to name the key and `--type` to specify whether it's for authentication or signing.

### Authentication Setup

When specifying SSH as the git protocol during login, GitHub CLI will detect existing SSH keys to upload, prompting to create and upload a new key if one is not found.

### Git Credential Configuration

The `gh auth setup-git` command configures git to use GitHub CLI as the credential helper for all authenticated hosts.

### Automatic Key Generation

GitHub CLI handles SSH key management automatically. You can run `gh ssh-key add path/to/key.pub` to upload a key manually.

### Using Existing Keys

If your local key is named something like `id_rsa` or `id_ed25519`, it will be picked automatically for any SSH connection. If your key has a non-standard filename, you will need to configure it explicitly in your `$HOME/.ssh/config` for github.com.


