## glab ssh-key add Overview

The `glab ssh-key add` command adds an SSH key to your GitLab account by creating a new SSH key owned by the currently authenticated user.

## Command Syntax

The basic syntax is `glab ssh-key add [key-file] [flags]`. The command requires the '--title' flag.

## Key Features and Flags

The command supports the following options:

- **Title**: The `-t, --title=""` flag specifies the new SSH key's title.
- **Expiration Date**: The `-e, --expires-at=""` flag sets the expiration date of the SSH key using ISO 8601 format: YYYY-MM-DDTHH:MM:SSZ.
- **Repository Selection**: The `-R, --repo=""` flag allows you to select another repository using either OWNER/REPO or GROUP/NAMESPACE/REPO format, and also accepts full URL or Git URL.

## Usage Examples

You can read an SSH key from stdin and upload it with `glab ssh-key add -t "my title"`, or read from a specified key file and upload with `glab ssh-key add ~/.ssh/id_ed25519.pub -t "my title"`.

## General SSH Key Management

The `glab ssh-key` command is used to manage SSH keys registered with your GitLab account.


